Reviewing `/Users/kenliu/Code/browser-comp/lib/capture-engine.mjs`. Here are the confirmed resource leak and error handling issues.

---

## Critical Issues

**Issue 1: Context leak on retry — confidence 100**

File: `/Users/kenliu/Code/browser-comp/lib/capture-engine.mjs`, lines 100-131 and 162-188

When any await inside the `captureWithRetry` callback throws after `browser.newContext()` has succeeded but before `context.close()` is reached, the context is abandoned. `captureWithRetry` catches the error at line 22 and either waits to retry or returns failure — neither path closes the leaked context. The context (and its underlying browser process resources) stays open for the lifetime of the browser object.

The specific failure points that trigger this:
- Line 105: `context.newPage()` throws — context created but never closed
- Lines 107-109: Eruda `addScriptTag` / `evaluate` throw — context and page open
- Line 112: `navigateAndSettle` throws (e.g., hard navigation timeout) — context and page open
- Line 116: `page.screenshot` throws — context and page open

Each retry creates a new context without closing the previous one. With `MAX_RETRIES = 3`, up to 2 leaked contexts accumulate per device before the final failure is returned. Across many devices this compounds.

Fix: wrap the body of the retry callback in try/finally:

```js
const result = await captureWithRetry(async () => {
  const context = await browser.newContext({ ... });
  try {
    const page = await context.newPage();
    // ... navigate, screenshot ...
    return { ... };
  } finally {
    await context.close();
  }
}, label);
```

---

**Issue 2: Browser process leak when an unhandled error escapes the device loop — confidence 95**

File: `/Users/kenliu/Code/browser-comp/lib/capture-engine.mjs`, lines 80 and 139

`browser.close()` at line 139 is only reached if the `for (const deviceName of deviceNames)` loop at line 82 completes normally. If any awaited call inside that loop throws an error that is not caught by `captureWithRetry` (e.g., `browser.newContext()` itself throws — this happens if the browser process has crashed or been killed mid-run), the exception propagates out of the `for` loop, skips line 139, and the browser process is leaked.

The same applies to the in-app loop: line 195 (`await browser.close()`) is skipped if `captureWithRetry` itself throws unexpectedly (e.g., a bug causes the retry loop to not return), or if `browser.newContext()` at line 163 throws before `captureWithRetry` even wraps it.

Fix: wrap each browser lifetime in try/finally:

```js
const browser = await browserConfig.launcher.launch({ headless: true });
try {
  for (const deviceName of deviceNames) {
    // ...
  }
} finally {
  await browser.close();
}
```

Apply the same pattern to the in-app browser block (lines 159-195).

---

**Issue 3: Crash when `browserConfig` is null in the in-app loop — confidence 90**

File: `/Users/kenliu/Code/browser-comp/lib/capture-engine.mjs`, line 157

At line 154, `BROWSER_LAUNCHERS[inApp.engine]` is assigned to `browserConfig` without a null check. Line 157 immediately dereferences `browserConfig.label` unconditionally. If `inApp.engine` is set to an engine string that has no entry in `BROWSER_LAUNCHERS` (e.g., due to a bad entry in `IN_APP_UA_STRINGS`), this throws `TypeError: Cannot read properties of null` at line 157, before the `continue` guard at line 150-152 has any chance to help (that guard only checks `inApp`, not `browserConfig`).

This contrasts with the standard browser loop at lines 73-77, which has an explicit `if (!browserConfig)` guard.

Fix: add the same guard used in the standard loop:

```js
const browserConfig = BROWSER_LAUNCHERS[inApp.engine];
if (!browserConfig) {
  console.warn(`  Unknown engine for in-app browser: ${key}, skipping`);
  continue;
}
```

---

## Summary

| # | Issue | Lines | Confidence |
|---|-------|-------|------------|
| 1 | Context leaked on every failed retry attempt | 100-131, 162-188 | 100 |
| 2 | Browser process leaked if device loop throws unexpectedly | 80/139, 159/195 | 95 |
| 3 | Unguarded `browserConfig.label` dereference in in-app loop | 154-157 | 90 |

Issue 1 is the most impactful in practice because it happens silently on every retry across normal network failures. Issue 2 is less frequent but results in orphaned browser OS processes that are never reaped within the process lifetime. Issue 3 is a straightforward missing null guard that matches the pattern already present elsewhere in the same function.

