## Code Review

Reviewing unstaged changes and the full codebase against CLAUDE.md guidelines (SOLID, KISS, YAGNI, DRY, no mixed responsibilities, no premature abstraction).

---

## Critical Issues

**Issue 1 - Resource leak on capture failure (real bug)**

Confidence: 95

File: `/Users/kenliu/Code/browser-comp/lib/capture-engine.mjs`, lines 100-131

Inside `captureWithRetry`, a browser context is opened but if `page.screenshot()` or `navigateAndSettle()` throws, `context.close()` on line 118 is never reached. The retry will then open another context on the same browser, leaking the previous one. After `MAX_RETRIES` failures the browser itself is eventually closed (cleaning up at the process level), but within a run with many devices this silently accumulates leaked contexts and can exhaust OS resources or interfere with later captures.

```js
// lines 100-131 — context.close() is only reached on the happy path
const result = await captureWithRetry(async () => {
  const context = await browser.newContext({ ... });
  const page = await context.newPage();
  // ... if anything below throws, context is never closed
  await navigateAndSettle(page, url, delay);
  await page.screenshot({ ... });
  await context.close();   // <-- skipped on exception
  return { ... };
}, label);
```

Fix: wrap the body in a try/finally so `context.close()` always executes:

```js
const context = await browser.newContext({ ... });
try {
  const page = await context.newPage();
  await navigateAndSettle(page, url, delay);
  await page.screenshot({ path: filepath, fullPage });
  return { ... };
} finally {
  await context.close();
}
```

The same pattern appears in the UA-spoof loop at lines 162-175.

---

**Issue 2 - Browser launched per in-app UA key instead of per engine (resource waste + real bug)**

Confidence: 88

File: `/Users/kenliu/Code/browser-comp/lib/capture-engine.mjs`, lines 159 and 195

In the UA-spoof loop a fresh browser is launched and then immediately closed for every individual UA key, even when multiple consecutive keys share the same engine (e.g., `facebook_ios`, `instagram_ios`, `tiktok_ios`, `wechat`, `line`, `twitter_ios`, `snapchat` all use `webkit`). This means WebKit is launched and torn down 7 times when `--ua-spoof facebook` is requested with all iOS variants. Beyond the performance hit, launching a browser inside a loop body that closes it at the end also means that if `browserConfig.launcher.launch()` throws (e.g., WebKit not installed), the error is uncaught and crashes the entire process without the graceful warning that the standard loop gives.

```js
// line 159 — launched fresh per key
const browser = await browserConfig.launcher.launch({ headless: true });
// ...
// line 195 — closed per key
await browser.close();
```

The standard-captures loop (lines 72-140) correctly lifts browser launch/close outside the device loop. The in-app loop should do the same, grouped by engine.

---

**Issue 3 - XSS via unsanitized URL injection into HTML (security bug)**

Confidence: 90

File: `/Users/kenliu/Code/browser-comp/lib/report-generator.mjs`, lines 39-42

The raw URL from CLI input is injected directly into the HTML output via `.replace('__URL__', config.url)`. A URL like `https://example.com</code><script>alert(1)</script><code>` would break out of the `<code>` element in the rendered report and execute arbitrary JavaScript. This matters even for a local tool because the generated report may be opened in a browser and shared.

```js
// line 39-42
const html = template
  .replace('__METADATA__', JSON.stringify(metadata))  // OK — goes into a JS string
  .replace('__URL__', config.url)                     // UNSAFE — raw HTML injection
  .replace('__DATE__', new Date().toLocaleString());  // low risk but same pattern
```

`__METADATA__` is fine because it is placed inside a JS `const` assignment and `JSON.stringify` escapes it. The URL and date are not escaped before being placed in HTML content.

Fix: HTML-encode the substitution values before injection:

```js
function escapeHtml(str) {
  return String(str)
    .replace(/&/g, '&amp;')
    .replace(/</g, '&lt;')
    .replace(/>/g, '&gt;')
    .replace(/"/g, '&quot;');
}

const html = template
  .replace('__METADATA__', JSON.stringify(metadata))
  .replace('__URL__', escapeHtml(config.url))
  .replace('__DATE__', escapeHtml(new Date().toLocaleString()));
```

The same vulnerability exists in the inline `generateDefaultTemplate()` fallback at line 80 of `report-generator.mjs`.

---

## Important Issues

**Issue 4 - No URL validation before capture (missing guard, process can hang)**

Confidence: 82

File: `/Users/kenliu/Code/browser-comp/capture.mjs`, lines 108-115 / `lib/capture-engine.mjs`, line 59

`captureScreenshots` validates that `url` is not null and exits, but it does not validate that the value is a valid URL. Passing a bare string like `node capture.mjs mysite` will hit `page.goto('mysite', ...)` and Playwright will throw a timeout error on every browser/device combination, burning 30 seconds per attempt times retries times devices. There is no early failure or user-friendly message.

A simple guard before any browser is launched would prevent the full matrix of failed captures:

```js
// At the top of captureScreenshots, after the null check
try { new URL(url); } catch {
  console.error('❌ Invalid URL. Example: node capture.mjs https://example.com');
  process.exit(1);
}
```

---

**Issue 5 - Mixed responsibility: captureScreenshots calls process.exit (SRP violation)**

Confidence: 83

File: `/Users/kenliu/Code/browser-comp/lib/capture-engine.mjs`, lines 59-63

`captureScreenshots` is a library function in `lib/`, but it calls `process.exit(1)` directly on invalid input. This couples the capture engine to the CLI runtime, makes the function untestable in isolation, and violates Single Responsibility. The validation and exit belong in the CLI entry point (`capture.mjs`) where config is assembled.

```js
// lines 59-63 — process.exit in a library module
if (!url) {
  console.error('❌ Please provide a URL as the first argument');
  console.error('Usage: node capture.mjs <url> [options]');
  process.exit(1);   // <-- should not be here
}
```

Fix: throw an error instead, and let `capture.mjs` catch it and call `process.exit`.

---

**Issue 6 - DRY violation: screenshot capture body duplicated verbatim for in-app captures**

Confidence: 85

File: `/Users/kenliu/Code/browser-comp/lib/capture-engine.mjs`, lines 100-131 vs lines 162-188

The inner logic of opening a context, creating a page, optionally injecting Eruda, navigating, screenshotting, and closing is substantially copy-pasted between the standard capture block and the UA-spoof block. The only differences are viewport/UA parameters and the result shape. CLAUDE.md explicitly flags DRY as a core rule.

Both blocks should call a shared helper, for example:

```js
async function captureOnce(browser, contextOptions, page, url, delay, filepath, fullPage) {
  const context = await browser.newContext(contextOptions);
  try {
    const p = await context.newPage();
    await navigateAndSettle(p, url, delay);
    await p.screenshot({ path: filepath, fullPage });
  } finally {
    await context.close();
  }
}
```

---

**Issue 7 - `createCard` uses innerHTML concatenation with unescaped result data (XSS in report)**

Confidence: 85

File: `/Users/kenliu/Code/browser-comp/report-template.html`, lines 479-501

`createCard` builds HTML strings using template literals that interpolate `result.browser`, `result.device`, `result.filename`, and `result.browserEngine` directly. All of these values originate from the captured metadata, which in turn comes from Playwright's device descriptors and in-app UA definitions. While the current device names and browser labels are safe, `result.device` and `result.browser` are ultimately strings that flow from user-controlled input (`--devices`, `--ua-spoof`). A device name containing `<script>` would execute in the report viewer.

```js
// lines 484-494 — unescaped interpolation into innerHTML
return `
  <div class="card ...">
    <div class="card-title">${result.browser}</div>       <!-- unsafe -->
    <div class="card-subtitle">${result.device}</div>     <!-- unsafe -->
    ...
    <img src="screenshots/${result.filename}" ...>        <!-- unsafe -->
  </div>
`;
```

Fix: use `textContent` assignment via `createElement`, or add an `escapeHtml` utility and apply it to every interpolated value before inserting into the template string.

